```c
#include <stdbool.h>

bool checkNum(int num) {
    if(num < 10000 || num > 99999)
        return false;

    int digit[10] = {0};
    int sum = 0;
    int rem;

    while(num != 0) {
        rem = num % 10;
        if(digit[rem] == 1) {  /* if the digit is repeating, return false */
            return false;
        } else {
            digit[rem] = 1;
        }

        sum += rem;
        num /= 10;
    }

    if(sum % 3 == 0) {
        return true;
    } else {
        return false;
    }
}
```
This C function works by taking an integer input and checks each digit of the number. 
- It first checks if the number is a five-digit number. If not, it returns false.
- Then it creates an array of 10 integers (for each digit 0 - 9) initialized to 0.
- It takes the last digit (remainder of the number divided by 10), and checks if the corresponding index in the digit array is already 1. This would mean that the digit has been repeated, in which case the function returns false.
- If the digit is not repeated, it marks the corresponding index in the digit array as 1 (meaning that the digit has been encountered), adds the digit to the sum, and removes the last digit from the number by integer division by 10.
- Finally, after all digits have been processed, it checks if the sum of the digits is divisible by 3. If so, it returns true; otherwise, it returns false.

