class Solution:
    def threeSumClosest(self, nums, target):
        nums.sort()  # Sort the array
        closest_sum = float('inf')  # Initialize closest sum to positive infinity
        for i in range(len(nums) - 2):
            left, right = i + 1, len(nums) - 1  # Two pointers approach
            while left < right:
                current_sum = nums[i] + nums[left] + nums[right]
                if abs(current_sum - target) < abs(closest_sum - target):
                    closest_sum = current_sum  # Update closest sum if current sum is closer to target
                if current_sum < target:
                    left += 1  # Move left pointer to the right
                elif current_sum > target:
                    right -= 1  # Move right pointer to the left
                else:
                    return current_sum  # Return early if the sum equals the target
        return closest_sum  # Return the closest sum found
```

The solution uses a three-pointer scanning algorithm to find the sum of three integers in the array that is closest to the target. It sorts the array and then uses two pointers to scan through the array, updating the closest sum as it goes. If the current sum equals the target, it returns early. Otherwise, it returns the closest sum found after scanning through the array.

