Here is a PHP-based solution that calculates the length of the maximal shared subsequence residing within two specific input strings:

```php
<?php

function maxSharedSubsequence($str1, $str2)
{
    $m = strlen($str1);
    $n = strlen($str2);
    $dp = array_fill(0, $m + 1, array_fill(0, $n + 1, 0));

    // Build in bottom up manner
    for ($i = 0; $i <= $m; $i++) {
        for ($j = 0; $j <= $n; $j++) {

            // If one string is empty, no subsequence will exist
            if ($i == 0 || $j == 0)
                $dp[$i][$j] = 0;
            // If last characters of the two strings match
            else if ($str1[$i - 1] == $str2[$j - 1])
                $dp[$i][$j] = $dp[$i - 1][$j - 1] + 1;
            // If last characters do not match
            else
                $dp[$i][$j] = max($dp[$i - 1][$j], $dp[$i][$j - 1]);
        }
    }

    // Length of the maximal shared subsequence
    return $dp[$m][$n];
}

$str1 = "abcdef";
$str2 = "azced";
echo "Length of maximal shared subsequence is " . maxSharedSubsequence($str1, $str2);

?>
```

In this PHP script, the `maxSharedSubsequence` function is defined which takes two strings as input. This function uses a two-dimensional dynamic programming array, `dp`, which is initialized with all entries as 0. 

Next, it fills up this `dp` array in a bottom-up manner. If the current pair of characters in both strings match, it increases the length of the found subsequence, otherwise, it keeps the maximum length found so far. 

Finally, it returns the length of the maximal shared subsequence, which is the last entry in the `dp` array.

Constructor chaining in Java allows you to call one constructor from another constructor in the same class or in a superclass. When dealing with multiple inheritance levels, including an abstract class, the constructors are chained in a hierarchical manner starting from the topmost superclass down to the subclass.

Let's consider an example to demonstrate constructor chaining in Java with multiple inheritance levels, including an abstract class.

```java
abstract class Animal {
    protected String name;

    public Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public abstract void makeSound();
}

class Mammal extends Animal {
    protected int age;

    public Mammal(String name, int age) {
        super(name);
        this.age = age;
    }

    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Mammal making sound");
    }
}

class Cat extends Mammal {
    protected String color;

    public Cat(String name, int age, String color) {
        super(name, age);
        this.color = color;
    }

    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Cat making sound");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Cat cat = new Cat("Kitty", 3, "Black");
        cat.makeSound();
    }
}
```

In the above example, we have an abstract class `Animal` that has a constructor taking a `name` parameter and an abstract method `makeSound()`. The `Mammal` class extends `Animal` and adds an `age` property and overrides the `makeSound()` method. Finally, the `Cat` class extends `Mammal` and adds a `color` property and overrides the `makeSound()` method.

When creating an instance of the `Cat` class, the constructors are chained in the following order:

1. `Cat(String name, int age, String color)` constructor is called.
2. It calls `super(name, age)` to invoke the `Mammal` constructor.
3. The `Mammal(String name, int age)` constructor calls `super(name)` to invoke the `Animal` constructor.
4. Finally, the `Animal(String name)` constructor is executed, completing the constructor chaining.

The output of the above code will be:

```
Cat making sound
```

Now, let's add a static factory method in the `Animal` class that returns an instance of a nested class `NestedClass`.

```java
abstract class Animal {
    protected String name;

    public Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public abstract void makeSound();

    public static NestedClass createNestedClass(int value) {
        return new NestedClass(value);
    }

    public static class NestedClass {
        private int value;

        public NestedClass(int value) {
            this.value = value;
        }

        public int getValue() {
            return value;
        }
    }
}

// Rest of the code remains the same
```

In the `Animal` class, we have added a static factory method `createNestedClass()` that returns an instance of the nested class `NestedClass`. This nested class has its own constructor and a method to get the value.

To incorporate the use of this nested class instance in constructor chaining, we can modify the `Cat` class constructor as follows:

```java
class Cat extends Mammal {
    protected String color;
    protected Animal.NestedClass nestedInstance;

    public Cat(String name, int age, String color) {
        super(name, age);
        this.color = color;
        this.nestedInstance = Animal.createNestedClass(10);
    }

    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Cat making sound");
    }
}
```

In the modified `Cat` class constructor, we call `Animal.createNestedClass(10)` to get an instance of the nested class `NestedClass` and assign it to the `nestedInstance` field.

By incorporating the nested class instance in constructor chaining, we can access and use it within the `Cat` class.

Note: In real-world scenarios, using constructor chaining with multiple inheritance levels and involving abstract classes may not always be the best design choice. It can make the code complex and harder to maintain. It is recommended to carefully design the class hierarchy and constructor chains to achieve better code clarity and maintainability.

Here's the implementation of the DoublyLinkedList class with the additional operations:

```cpp
class DoublyLinkedList {
private:
    struct Node {
        int data;
        Node* prev;
        Node* next;

        Node(int value) : data(value), prev(nullptr), next(nullptr) {}
    };

    Node* head;
    Node* tail;
    int size;

public:
    DoublyLinkedList() {
        head = new Node(0);
        tail = new Node(0);
        head->next = tail;
        tail->prev = head;
        size = 0;
    }

    ~DoublyLinkedList() {
        clear();
        delete head;
        delete tail;
    }

    void insertFront(int value) {
        Node* newNode = new Node(value);
        newNode->prev = head;
        newNode->next = head->next;
        head->next->prev = newNode;
        head->next = newNode;
        size++;
    }

    void insertEnd(int value) {
        Node* newNode = new Node(value);
        newNode->next = tail;
        newNode->prev = tail->prev;
        tail->prev->next = newNode;
        tail->prev = newNode;
        size++;
    }

    void deleteNode(int value) {
        Node* curr = head->next;
        while (curr != tail) {
            if (curr->data == value) {
                curr->prev->next = curr->next;
                curr->next->prev = curr->prev;
                delete curr;
                size--;
                return;
            }
            curr = curr->next;
        }
    }

    void reverse() {
        Node* curr = head;
        Node* temp = nullptr;
        while (curr != nullptr) {
            temp = curr->prev;
            curr->prev = curr->next;
            curr->next = temp;
            curr = curr->prev;
        }
        if (temp != nullptr) {
            head = temp->prev;
        }
    }

    int getKthFromEnd(int k) {
        if (k > size) {
            return -1;
        }
        Node* curr = tail->prev;
        while (k > 1) {
            curr = curr->prev;
            k--;
        }
        return curr->data;
    }

    void sort() {
        mergeSort(head->next, tail->prev);
    }

    void mergeSort(Node* start, Node* end) {
        if (start != end) {
            Node* mid = getMiddle(start, end);
            mergeSort(start, mid);
            mergeSort(mid->next, end);
            merge(start, mid, end);
        }
    }

    Node* getMiddle(Node* start, Node* end) {
        Node* slow = start;
        Node* fast = start;
        while (fast != end && fast->next != end) {
            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next->next;
        }
        return slow;
    }

    void merge(Node* start, Node* mid, Node* end) {
        DoublyLinkedList mergedList;
        Node* left = start;
        Node* right = mid->next;
        while (left != mid->next && right != end->next) {
            if (left->data <= right->data) {
                mergedList.insertEnd(left->data);
                left = left->next;
            } else {
                mergedList.insertEnd(right->data);
                right = right->next;
            }
        }
        while (left != mid->next) {
            mergedList.insertEnd(left->data);
            left = left->next;
        }
        while (right != end->next) {
            mergedList.insertEnd(right->data);
            right = right->next;
        }
        Node* curr = start;
        Node* mergedCurr = mergedList.head->next;
        while (curr != end->next) {
            curr->data = mergedCurr->data;
            curr = curr->next;
            mergedCurr = mergedCurr->next;
        }
    }

    DoublyLinkedList merge(DoublyLinkedList list) {
        DoublyLinkedList mergedList;
        Node* curr1 = head->next;
        Node* curr2 = list.head->next;
        while (curr1 != tail && curr2 != list.tail) {
            if (curr1->data <= curr2->data) {
                mergedList.insertEnd(curr1->data);
                curr1 = curr1->next;
            } else {
                mergedList.insertEnd(curr2->data);
                curr2 = curr2->next;
            }
        }
        while (curr1 != tail) {
            mergedList.insertEnd(curr1->data);
            curr1 = curr1->next;
        }
        while (curr2 != list.tail) {
            mergedList.insertEnd(curr2->data);
            curr2 = curr2->next;
        }
        return mergedList;
    }

    void print() {
        Node* curr = head->next;
        while (curr != tail) {
            cout << curr->data << " ";
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        cout << endl;
    }

    void clear() {
        Node* curr = head->next;
        while (curr != tail) {
            Node* temp = curr;
            curr = curr->next;
            delete temp;
        }
        head->next = tail;
        tail->prev = head;
        size = 0;
    }
};
```

