The problem here is that the ans vector is created for each function call. So when the function ends, the vector ans is lost along with its values. Because of that, it's never taken into account outside of the function where it was created. You do not have any persistent data storage here.

If you declare `vector<int> ans` globally, it is available and persistent for all function calls and updated throughout, rather than being confined to a single function call. That's why it gives correct output when `vector<int> ans` is declared globally. 

