```C++
#include <iostream>

// The Fibonacci sequence is typically defined with its two first terms being 0 and 1.
// The sequence is calculated by summing up the two preceding numbers. 
// To optimize time and space, we can calculate the Fibonacci sequence iteratively rather than recursively.

// Use long long int as it can store up to 18 digit number, thus it can store upto 93 Fibonacci numbers.
long long fibonacciNum[50];
int fib_index = 2; // The index to control writing fibonacci numbers to the array.

// Error handling variables, these variables initiate as 'false'.
// If an error occurs in running the program, the variable corresponding to that error will turn to 'true'.
bool overflow_error = false;
bool memory_error = false;

// Function to calculate & store first 50 Fibonacci numbers in an array.
void calculateFibonacci() 
{
    fibonacciNum[0] = 0;
    fibonacciNum[1] = 1;

    while(fib_index < 50)
    {
        // Calculating the next Fibonacci number.
        fibonacciNum[fib_index] = fibonacciNum[fib_index - 1] + fibonacciNum[fib_index - 2];

        /* 
            Overflow check: If it is less than any of previous two numbers than overflow has occured 
        */
        if(fibonacciNum[fib_index] < fibonacciNum[fib_index - 1] || fibonacciNum[fib_index] < fibonacciNum[fib_index - 2] )
        {
            overflow_error = true;
            break;
        }

        fib_index++;
    }
}

int main() 
{
    try
    {
        calculateFibonacci();

        if (overflow_error)
            throw std::overflow_error("Overflow error occured");

        long long sum = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < fib_index; i++)
        {
            // Print the Fibonacci sequence.
            std::cout << "Fibonnaci number " << i << " " << fibonacciNum[i] << "\n";
            if(fibonacciNum[i] % 5 == 0) sum += fibonacciNum[i];
        }

        std::cout << "Sum of fibonacci numbers that are divisible by 5 is " << sum << "\n";

    }
    catch(std::overflow_error& e)
    {
        std::cerr << "Caught overflow exception: " << e.what() << std::endl;
    }
    catch(...)
    {
        std::cerr << "Unknown exception caught" << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Key optimizations in the program include:
1. Instead of using recursion to find Fibonacci numbers which takes exponential time complexity, we're using a loop with linear time complexity.
2. We're storing Fibonacci numbers in an array to avoid recalculating them, saving time.
3. We're checking for overflow, which can corrupt memory and affect the correctness of code.
4. We're handling exceptions and catching overflow errors to increase the robustness of code.

Note: Most modern computers should handle this program easily, but the Fibonacci sequence grows pretty fast, and even 64-bit unsigned integers can hold only up to the 94th Fibonacci number.

