One way to remove duplicates from an array while maintaining the original order of elements is by using the `filter()` method along with the `indexOf()` method. Here's an example solution that satisfies the given time and space complexity:

```javascript
let myArr = [1, 2, 3, 1, 4, 3];

function removeDuplicates(arr) {
  return arr.filter((element, index) => arr.indexOf(element) === index);
}

let result = removeDuplicates(myArr);
console.log(result); // [1, 2, 3, 4]
```

In this solution, the `filter()` method is used to iterate through each element of the array. The callback function passed to `filter()` checks if the index of the current element (`arr.indexOf(element)`) is equal to the current index (`index`). If they are equal, it means that this is the first occurrence of the element in the array, so it is kept in the filtered result.

The `indexOf()` method is used to find the first occurrence of an element in the array. Since `indexOf()` has a time complexity of O(n), and we are calling it within the `filter()` method, the overall time complexity of this solution is O(n^2).

The space complexity of this solution is O(1) because it doesn't require any additional memory beyond the filtered array itself.

