A binary search algorithm is used to find the position of a specific value in a sorted array. It is more efficient than linear searches as it repeatedly divides the array in half until the desired value has been found. Here's how to execute a binary search algorithm using C#:

1. Specify your array and the value that you're searching for.
2. Initialize two variables as pointers, representing the lower and upper limits of the search range (start and end).
3. Start a while loop that continues as long as the 'start' is less than or equal to 'end'.
4. Calculate the mid-point of the array.
5. If the mid-point equals the search value, then you've found the desired value and can return its position.
6. If the mid-point is less than the search value, adjust the start pointer to be one position to the right of the mid-point.
7. If the mid-point is greater than the search value, adjust the end pointer to be one position to the left of the mid-point.
8. If the value isn't found, return -1 or a similar indicator of failure.

Here's the C# code:

```C#
public static int BinarySearch(int[] array, int searchValue)
{
    int start = 0;
    int end = array.Length - 1;

    while (start <= end)
    {
        int mid = start + (end - start) / 2;

        if (array[mid] == searchValue)
        {
            return mid;
        }

        if (array[mid] < searchValue)
        {
            start = mid + 1;
        }
        else
        {
            end = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    return -1;  // return -1 or any appropriate value indicating not found
}
```

